AGI - There is a surgeon, a nun and a riot. Although the incipit recalls those of certain jokes, the intentions of the former mayor of Rome Ignazio Marino> are very serious: running for the European elections, head of the Italian Centre with the redundant, being elected and staying in Brussels to carry out the battles for climate, peace and, above all, for migrants. Thank you for being here so numerous, thanks to Nicola Fratoianni and Angelo Bonelli > for the invitation to run for the European elections. "When I returned to the United States to do my surgeon's job, I told my sister friend that if I had come up with the idea of re-candidate me, he had to shoot me in the calf with a small caliber weapon, where it hurts, but it does not bring irreparable damage such as, for example, to the thigh," begins Marino at the press conference organized in the new headquarters of the Foreign Press in Rome, in that Palazzo Grazioli >che is residence
A few tens of meters there is the Senate Palace, greeted by Marino in 2013 after the notary distrust of the councillors Pd and that, more political, of the left. The same left with which today the 'Martian mayor' returns to the field. Despite the determination not to fall, Marino has recently been brought to reflect. It happened the day of the Superbowl when, says Marino, "more than 150 million Americans are glued to the TV. No one works, let alone American senators. On the other hand, on 11 February, the American Senate met to vote for 85 billion arms and non-health expenditure or public school.' And here is the first of the three themes that led Marino to choose to apply: "Cardinal Martini wrote from Jerusalem that if each people only look at their own pain, revenge will always prevail. Giving voice to others' pain is the premise of every future perspective of peace. How can we accept that in the face of an unacceptable violence like that of October seven, the answer can be 33 thousand dead? Two thousand children who have lost at least one arto.&nbsp; Europe in the face of all this seems lost as a bowl of coconut between two continents, instead it must resume its function and its value".
The second theme is the environment: "The environmental issue is dramatic," says Marino: "In Miami, this step, most of the territory will soon be underwater."
And here is the third theme, strongly connected with the climate crisis: "The Fiji Islands have welcomed the inhabitants of the Tuvalu archipelago already submerged by the waters. They welcomed and trained them to lead a dignified life elsewhere."
<div </div
&nbsp;
The Fijis have done so, it should also do Europe, it is the reasoning of Marino. "If I am elected one of the issues in which I want to engage, it is that of immigration management," insisting on changing Dublin and other countries' agreements. The Repatriation Centres are the same as the images of judicial psychiatric hospitals. We cannot treat people who escape from war, violence and rape, building walls and putting naval blocks. We need rules shared with the whole European continent. I think it is right to take this step to try to help our society."
First, however, we must be elected. Angelo Bonelli, one of the two leaders of the alliance, is sure to be able to overcome the disembarkation of 4 percent.
The alliance with the Italian Left, therefore, seems to work. In fact, as Fratoianni says, the two represent "the only couple that today really works in politics". It does not escape, however, that before and above all after the European Avs, and therefore also Marino, will find themselves having to dialogue precisely with that Pd that denied its mayor. A different Pd than that led by Renzi, > in some ways to antipods. Today there is Schlein al Nazareno.> With the secretary, Bonelli and Fratoianni started a collaboration on many issues, from health to minimum wage. Marino, however, does not seem convinced of the current change and warns: "Schlein seems to me to be a very articulated woman in the apparent his thought, but it counts how you translate your words into vows. They don't count the statements in the newspapers as much as those in parliament. I want to see how they can be compared to the increase of two percent of GDP on arms and compared to the three hundred billion less in health from 2002 to today." Other than "I'll be back" >- "I will return" - as the former mayor says quoting the beloved Schwarzenegger in Terminator. Ignazio Marino has already returned.&nbsp;
