AGI -&nbsp;"If there are third and impartial journalists is an account, but if there are journalists who are actually opinionists, who more than asking questions offer answers, they have to fall into the rules of the par condicio like politicians. Or it is argued that in the election campaign only politicians are confronted in the various programmes of study, or there must be rules that guarantee anyone who participates in doing so in accordance with the rules on pluralism." Maria Elena Boschi reiterated on Libero her proposal to change the discipline on the par condicio so as to "ensure that citizens can form their opinion freely and all candidates can have the same opportunities in view of the vote".
<br> "I do not see why &nbsp;- added MP Iv - it should apply only to political representatives and not to anyone who can, with their own political opinions, influence citizens, even significantly. Moreover, my proposal is to write in the resolution of the Rai Vigilance at least what the Agcom resolution provides for, that is, it is necessary to consider for the purposes of the par condicio 'any person clearly attributable to the parties or to the competing lists &nbsp; and also the 'positions of political content expressed by subjects and people not directly involved in the electoral competition".
<br> Therefore, apply the links of the par condicio in Rai also to journalists so as to "shape the veil of hypocrisy".
&nbsp;
"It is clear that commentators can influence public opinion as political representatives. On the contrary, perhaps more, because&nbsp;- he found Boschi - playing on the role of apparent tertience some risk being more convincing than many politicians, not to mention that some opinionists have now become real television characters and social have many followers". "For a long time TV broadcasts invite journalists to support different political thesis, everyone knows. And then - re-launch - why &nbsp;not do it transparently and regulated at least in period of par condicio?" &nbsp;

